V 20 Nb 20 Mo 20 Ta 20 W 20 alloy Compressive engineering stressestrain curves for the V 20 Nb 20 Mo 20 Ta 20 W 20 alloy are shown in Fig.  2 . At rt (Fig.  2a ), the alloy showed a yield stress s 0.2 ¼ 1246 MPa and a maximum (peak) stress strength of s m ¼ 1270 MPa
An increase in temperature to 600 C decreased the yield stress to s 0.2 ¼ 862 MPa, but increased total compressive failure strain to 3 f z 13%.
With a further increase in the temperature to 1000 C, s 0.2 slightly decreased to 842 MPa and 3 f increased to 19%.
An increase in the temperature to 1200 C led to a noticeable decrease in s 0.2 (to 735 MPa), 3 f (to w8%).
The average grain size in the Nb 25 Mo 25 Ta 25 W 25 alloy was 200 mm.

In the Nb 25 Mo 25 Ta 25 W 25 alloy, the yield stress was 561 MPa at 600 C and it continuously decreased with temperature down to 405 MPa at 1600 C. The V 20 Nb 20 Mo 20 Ta 20 W 20 alloy was w200 MPa stronger in the temperature range of 600 C e 1200 C. However, the yield stress of the V 20 Nb 20 Mo 20 Ta 20 W 20 alloy decreased more rapidly than that of the Nb 25 Mo 25 Ta 25 W 25 alloy in the temperature range of 1200 C e 1600 C, so that its yield stress at 1600 C (477 MPa) was close to that of the Nb 25 Mo 25 Ta 25 W 25 alloy (405 MPa).
